{"type":"style","rule":"Use 'on' for impersonal/general statements, 'nous' sparingly for rhetorical emphasis. Maintain consistent voice throughout."}
{"type":"style","rule":"Avoid 'qui...qui' chains. Use present participles to break repetition."}
{"type":"style","rule":"Keep well-known English technical terms (e.g., 'forward pass', 'sleep-time agents') rather than creating awkward literal translations."}
{"type":"style","en":"pourvu que vs si","rule":"Use 'si' for simple conditions; 'pourvu que' for provisions/provisos."}
{"type":"style","rule":"Prefer verb forms over nominalizations: 'ils branchent, bouclent' not 'ils font du branchement, des boucles'."}
{"type":"style","en":"series/part numbering","rule":"Use 'Partie N/M' format (e.g., 'Partie 1/2').","avoid":"1re partie/2 or Nème partie"}
{"type":"style","rule":"Avoid starting sentences with 'Mais' repeatedly. Use 'Cela dit,' or embed 'quand même' in sentence."}
{"type":"style","rule":"When translating quotes from external sources, preserve key adverbs like 'dynamiquement'."}
{"type":"style","rule":"Avoid redundant etymological pairs: don't use 'reconstruction' near 'reconstituer'."}
{"type":"style","rule":"Avoid triple gerund chains ('en X, en Y, et en Z'). Fold two ideas together when possible."}
{"type":"style","rule":"Avoid verb anglicisms like 'seeker'. Use native French verbs ('se positionner')."}
